 This brings the positivity rate to 1.7 per cent, up from Sunday’s 1.2%. “37 are Kenyans while 18 are foreigners. 34 are males and 21 are females. The youngest is a six-month-old child while the oldest is 92 years,” Health Cabinet Secretary Mutahi Kagwe said in a statement on Monday. This brings the total number of cases recorded since the virus hit the country in 2020 to 322,151 out of the 3,261,313 tests conducted so far. Nairobi County leads with the highest number of cases (47) while the others are distributed as follows: Nyeri 3, Mombasa 2, Kiambu 1, Kisii 1 and Laikipia 1. CS Kagwe further noted 137 recoveries, 121 of whom are from the Home-Based Isolation and Care program while 16 are from various health facilities countrywide. Total recoveries stand at 296,108 out of which 243,493 are from the Home-Based Care and Isolation program and 52,615 from various facilities. No new deaths have been recorded  and total fatalities still stand at 5,621. On the ongoing vaccination exercise, the ministry noted that 13,782,963 vaccines had been administered across the country as of February 6. Of these, 6,965,069 are partially vaccinated while those fully vaccinated are 6,338,847 “Proportion of adults fully vaccinated was 23.3%. The Government is working towards vaccinating a targeted population of 27,246,033,” said Kagwe.